    "author_association": "NONE",
    "body": "### Problem\r\n\r\nWhen I try to use `gcc` to comment or uncomment a line in a C++ file, it doesn't work at all. I thought that, by default, the `commentstring` option which C uses (`/*%s*/`)  was supposed to be used in C++ files, but I get nothing but the message \"Option 'commentstring' is empty.\" I only get this problem on Windows. On macOS it works as I expected.\r\n\r\n### Steps to reproduce\r\n\r\n`nvim --clean`\r\n`:e test.cpp`\r\nType something.\r\n`gcc`\r\nProduces: \"Option 'commentstring' is empty.\"\r\n\r\n### Expected behavior\r\n\r\nI was under the impression that C++ used the same `commentstring` option as C, but it doesn't seem to be the case for some reason.\r\n\r\n### Neovim version (nvim -v)\r\n\r\nNeovim version v0.10.0\r\n\r\n### Vim (not Nvim) behaves the same?\r\n\r\nNo, Vim sets `commentstring` in the way I expected it to.\r\n\r\n### Operating system/version\r\n\r\nWindows 10\r\n\r\n### Terminal name/version\r\n\r\nAlacritty version 0.13.2 (bb8ea18)\r\n\r\n### $TERM environment variable\r\n\r\nxterm-256color\r\n\r\n### Installation\r\n\r\nInstalled with winget",
